        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='89004' id='6' story-point-id='1' type-v2='text' w='100098' x='0' y='11618'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontsize='26'>QB NIL ROI in College Football</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='26'>Are programs converting premium quarterback value into wins?</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='26'>Jack Petti</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='26'>ISA 401 Final Project</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='83402' hidden='true' id='7' story-point-id='2' type-v2='text' w='100197' x='98' y='14627'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontsize='23'>NIL has changed college football by making roster construction more financially driven.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='23'>Donors, collectives, and athletic departments now face a key question: does premium player investment actually translate into wins?</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='23'>Because actual NIL payments are private, this project uses public On3 quarterback NIL valuations as a proxy for premium player investment.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='87137' hidden='true' id='8' story-point-id='3' type-v2='text' w='100098' x='98' y='13485'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontsize='22'>Data Sources</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='22'>• On3 public quarterback NIL valuation table</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='22'>• ESPN public scoreboard data for overall wins and losses</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='22'>• Sports Reference / team performance data used in the project pipeline</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='22'>Important Limitation</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='22'>This project does not claim to know actual NIL payments. The NIL field represents public quarterback NIL valuation, not confirmed school spending.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='22'>Players without a listed NIL valuation were kept in the raw manual file but excluded from the main ROI visuals.</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
        <zone flipboard-zone-id='5' forceUpdate='true' h='80809' hidden='true' id='9' story-point-id='9' type-v2='text' w='99705' x='98' y='14834'>
          <formatted-text>
            <run fontsize='20'>Final Takeaways</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='20'>1. Public QB NIL valuation is connected to expectations, but it does not guarantee winning.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='20'>2. Some programs generated stronger returns than expected, meaning they won more than the model predicted based on QB NIL value.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='20'>3. Other programs fell short despite having high public QB NIL valuations, showing that a high-value quarterback alone is not enough.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='20'>4. The best NIL strategy is not simply chasing the highest-valued quarterback. Programs also need strong coaching, roster depth, offensive line play, defense, and player development.</run>
            <run>Æ&#10;&#10;</run>
            <run fontsize='20'>5. For donors and athletic departments, the key question is not just “How much are we spending?” but “Are we converting premium player value into wins?”</run>
          </formatted-text>
        </zone>
      </zones>
      <simple-id uuid='{BC49A8C0-3E96-44E2-8B66-25262E2181C1}' />
    </dashboard>
  </dashboards>
